climbs.name: Tourette's Syndrome
climbs.fa: Jack Roberts, Pam Ranger, Alan Bartlett & Bob Harrington, January 1990

content.description: Face climb seams 5' right of Marmac's Crack to the right end of the ledge.  Move right and follow another thin crack to the top.
3 bolts and small to medium gear.  At top, climb up and over one boulder, step across to another boulder to rap anchor.

climbs.name: Siamese
climbs.fa: Bob Gaines and Frank Bentwood, Dec. 2009

content.description:
Look for this short cliff on the right as you enter the Cathouse canyon.

Same start as Alley Cat, then move right to a bolt and make a delicate traverse (5.8) to the right. Climb straight up past another bolt (5.7) up to a 2 bolt belay/rappel anchor.
content.protection: You can get a very small CD (oo metolious) before the first bolt.

content.description: Climb the crack with good rock. crux is probably halfway up. leave the crack and scramble up and left on chossy rock. you will go thru a slot, turn right, and reach the top
content.location:
This crack is near the right side of the formation.

there is a shelf at the base of the crack.

to descend, walk west along the top of the formation, downclimb easy terrain(continuing west)until you come to a dropoff. down climb a third class slot which puts you on a boulder. down climb another slot(fourth class)on the right side of said boulder. at the bottom of the slot, turn

left until you reach the southside of the formation

content.description: This route climbs the actual dihedral crack that is the far right perimeter of Lower Cathouse. Prominent bush at the base. Very chossy rock with some loose blocks halfway up, but the climbing itself is fairly enjoyable with good moves pulling over the chockstone.
content.protection: Medium to large gear, especially for anchor

climbs.name: Not that good, but not that bad either

content.description: Start down in the pit to the left of Chicken Pox, go up crack, transition to climb arete/face, and finish same as Chicken Pox
Mantle onto a slab then pull through some manky horizontal cracks. Clip a lone bolt before moving into a finger to thin hands crack for a few moves.
content.location: The line left of cat scratch fever. Climbs through an easily identifiable pod.

content.description: This climbs a crack, just right of the center of the Left Side face. From the right side of the face, walk left on a ramp/ledge to this crack. The crack doesn't quite reach the ledge and another crack runs parallel to it up higher. The rock is good. Follow this crack to a ledge, with a wide crack to the left an a hand crack to the right. Follow the crack on the right to the top.

This route, also on the Left Side face, starts about 10' right of "Felix". Make some moves up to the ledge, step left and follow face and a right curving flake/crack, then a few  feet up a vertical crack. Move left to another crack. Follow this and face to the top.
On the Left Side Face, climb the start to "Little Brown Jug" to the first ledge. Step to the right to two parallel thin cracks. Follow these and the crack and face above.
One bolt protects opening move, climb up and over roof.  Large gear for anchor, rap off sidestep.

The leftmost bolted line on the "right" wall.  Identified by 4 bolts beginning about a third of the way up the wall.  The opening moves to reach the first bolt are fun, but then the climbing gets contrived as you can basically touch other climbs on either side of you.
content.protection: 4 bolts + some protection for the first horizontal, 2 bolt anchor/rap.

content.description: This route climbs the leftmost crack on the right formation.  Scramble up some flakes to gain the crack itself which in the beginning is a bit shallow.  Plenty of foot holds gain help one gain the upper crack of the route.

This climbs the blunt arete on the right edge of the face. From a ledge, climb unprotected face to a crack about halfway up. This crack is off route, but  stoppers and small cams can be used to protect about another 10 feet. Continue to the top. One can also top rope or solo the arete without the crack.
content.protection: Pro to 1". Safest to top rope.

content.description: Right of Highstep, climb the dogleg crack, and rap off Sidestep
Climb the face between Felix and Little Brown Jug

This climbs an easy crack on the left side of the Left Side face. Starting off a boulder, make a few moves to a ledge. Continue up the crack to the west shoulder of the cliff. You can end the climb here or continue up easy climbing to the top. If you want anchors on top you will need some 3"-3.5" cams.
Climbs a right-facing corner down low, passes over a small roof about 1/3 of the way up and finishes with a hand crack.
content.location:
Located down and left from

Heathcliff

.

content.description:
Climb

Hello Kitty

to the horizontal break, then cut right to climb the narrow face between that route and

Nine Lives

.
content.location:
The narrow face between

Hello Kitty

and

Nine Lives

.

content.description:
Look for this short cliff on the right as you enter the Cathouse canyon.

Slab with 2 bolts to steeper moves past one more bolt.
Climb fun, short Dihedral Crack left of Highstep, rap off Sidestep
20 feet of steep hueco's 2 bolts than mixed low angled face and crack.
content.protection: 2 bolts and small cams. Rap off existing anchors on the left.
content.location: Approach from the right end of the boulder pile up to the small tree right below the climb.

content.description: Rightmost bolted line on the right wall.  Up and over the low roof (crux) to two bolts.  A final piece of gear will see you to the top.  Perhaps the best line on the wall.
content.protection: Yellow alien + medium nuts + 2 bolts for the route.  #1-#3 camalots for the anchor.

climbs.name: Casa del Gato
climbs.fa: Todd Swain, Allen Steck, John Thackray, Joe Fitschen 11-2005

content.description: The climb ascends a small buttress between the two main Cathouse formations. Either climb a crack up the right center of the buttress or start six feet right on the right edge of the buttress and climb a crack that runs up onto the arête. When the crack ends, climb up and left on the face to the top (PG13).
content.location: The climb ascends a small buttress between the two main Cathouse formations.

climbs.name: Bobcat
climbs.fa: (TR) Chris Miller, January 1999, First Lead: Bob Gaines and Frank Bentwood, Dec. 2009

content.description: Climb the patina face (2 bolts) between Tourette's Syndrome and Garfield, finishing up a thin crack (which is the top section of Tourette's) then step left and climb a slab to the top.
content.protection:
2 bolts, CDs .4 to 3 inches.

For the top anchor you can sling a small pinnacle, and back it up with a #2 camalot.

content.description: Look for this short cliff on the right as you enter the Cathouse canyon. This is the crack on the left side.
content.protection: To 4 inches. 2 bolt rap anchor located a short downclimb from the top.
